The Telegraph - Calcutta : Bengal
Archives
				 Panel amp; promise to placate dealers
 A STAFF REPORTER																								Calcutta, Oct. 23: Buddhadeb Bhattacharjee today promised security to ration dealers and a panel to look into their other demands. 																								The chief ministers assurances made the dealers take back licences that they had surrendered en masse yesterday.																								The government will form a committee chaired by the director-general of food and supplies to look into the dealers demands.																								It will also have members of the rationing directorate and a representative each from the two major dealers bodies  the Modified Rationing Dealers Association and the Ration Shop Owners Association. 																								The committee will consider the demand for a hike in the commission on wheat, rice and sugar as well as an increase in the transportation cost of commodities. It will submit its recommendations in two months, food minister Paresh Adhikary said.																								The chief minister has promised us security. He has spoken to the chief secretary and the director-general of police regarding this. Weve decided to take back our licences, said Biswambar Basu of the shop owners association.																								The minister, however, said surrendering licence was illegal 																								Mamata Banerjee would not back SUCIs 12-hour bandh on October 30 to protest against corruption in the public distribution system.																								Ration dealer Hasan Ali, 50, died of a heart attack in Murshidabads Bhagabangola last night. His brother said he died because of tension following the attack on dealers across Bengal.
